******
[3] South Korea (North Jeolla)
Date: Tue 8 Apr 2008
Source: The Dong-A Ilbo [edited]
<http://english.donga.com/srv/service.php3?bicode=040000&biid=2008040808038>


Virulent bird flu strain confirmed in Jeongeup
----------------------------------------------
Highly pathogenic avian influenza is confirmed to have broken out in
the southwestern city of Jeongeup, the 2nd after one on a chicken
farm in Gimje, North Jeolla Province.

The Food, Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries Ministry announced
Monday [7 Apr 2008] that the H5N1 strain of the bird flu virus killed
ducks on a farm in the town of Yeongwon near Jeongeup as reported
Thursday [3 Apr 2008].

The number of poultry farms with or suspected of having bird flu has
increased to 4 after the 1st outbreak was confirmed in a chicken farm
in the town of Yeongji last week.

Quarantine authorities of North Jeolla Province examined a duck farm
in the town of Gobu, where 700 of the birds died Saturday [5 Apr
2008]. They suspect the possibility of a H5N1 outbreak.

The farm is only 4.5 km (3 mi) away from where the virus was first
detected. Bird flu symptoms such as bleeding in the kidney were found
among ducks in the 1st autopsy.

Health authorities prohibited 18 000 ducks from the Gobu farm from
being carried out and are considering culling them.

Fine Korea, a duck butchery in Naju, South Jeolla Province, has
culled 6520 ducks from Yeongwon. The company has been ordered to bury
30 000 out of 90 000 slaughtered over the past 2 to 5 days, including
the ducks it culled. 60 000 of the dead ducks are being collected as
they are already on the market. Kim Chang-seop, the ministry's
director for animal disease prevention, said, "Though ducks on the
market are not directly related to avian influenza, we are collecting
them because they might have been contaminated by the butchery
machine. Even if they were contaminated, their meat is safe."

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[South Korea's immediate notification on the 1st focus of this
developing HPAI epizootic was submitted to the OIE on Wed 2 Apr 2008;
the report mentioned the identity of the involved serotype as
"pending". Today's (8 Apr 2008) confirmation of H5N1 and details of
the additional foci, including duck plants, are expected to be
described in the due follow-up report. - Mod.AS]
